[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] In ray tracing, rays are often modeled as geometric ray with no thickness to perform efficient geometric queries such as a ray-triangle intersection.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] From a physics of light transport point of view, however, this is an inaccurate model provided the pixel on the sensor plane has non-zero area.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] In the simplified pinhole camera optics model, the energy reaching the pixel comes from the integral of radiance from the solid angle by which the sensor pixel sees the scene through the pinhole at the focal plane.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] This yields the key notion of **pixel footprint** on surfaces or in the texture space, which is the back projection of the pixel on to the scene.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Note that this approach can also represent a lens-based camera and thus depth of field effects, using a cone whose cross-section decreases from the lens size to zero at the focal plane, and then increases.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Real optical system do not focus on exact points because of diffraction and imperfections.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] This can be modeled with a point spread function (PSF) weighted within a solid angle larger than the pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] The physically based image formation model can be approximated by the convolution with the point spread function assuming the function is shift-invariant and linear.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] In practice, techniques such as multisample anti-aliasing estimate this cone-based model by oversampling the signal and then performing a convolution (the reconstruction filter).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] The backprojected cone footprint onto the scene can also be used to directly pre-filter the geometry and textures of the scene.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Note that contrary to intuition, the reconstruction filter should not be the pixel footprint (as the pinhole camera model would suggest), since a box filter has poor spectral properties.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Conversely, the ideal sinc function is not practical, having infinite support with possibly negative values which often creates ringing artifacts due to the Gibbs phenomenon.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] A Gaussian or a Lanczos filter are considered good compromises.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Cone and Beam early papers rely on different simplifications: the first considers a circular section and treats the intersection with various possible shapes.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] The second treats an accurate pyramidal beam through the pixel and along a complex path, but it only works for polyhedrical shapes.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Cone tracing solves certain problems related to sampling and aliasing, which can plague conventional ray tracing.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] However, cone tracing creates a host of problems of its own.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] For example, just intersecting a cone with scene geometry leads to an enormous variety of possible results.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] For this reason, cone tracing has remained mostly unpopular.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] In recent years, increases in computer speed have made Monte Carlo algorithms like distributed ray tracing - i.e. stochastic explicit integration of the pixel - much more used than cone tracing because the results are exact provided enough samples are used.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] But the convergence is so slow that even in the context of off-line rendering a huge amount of time can be required to avoid noise.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Differential cone-tracing, considering a differential angular neighborhood around a ray, avoids the complexity of exact geometry intersection but requires a LOD representation of the geometry and appearance of the objects.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] MIPmapping is an approximation of it limited to the integration of the surface texture within a cone footprint.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Differential ray-tracing extends it to textured surfaces viewed through complex paths of cones reflected or refracted by curved surfaces.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Raymarching methods over signed distance fields (SDFs) naturally allow easy use of cone-like tracing, at zero additional cost to the tracing, and both speeds up tracing and improves quality.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] Voxel cone tracing is a real-time algorithm that uses a hierarchical voxel representation of scene geometry, such as a sparse voxel octree, to support fast cone tracing for indirect illumination.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/cone-tracing] This approach allows for the approximation of effects like glossy reflections and ambient occlusion at interactive framerates without the need for precomputation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] An **octree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly eight children.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Octrees are most often used to partition a three-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into eight octants.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Octrees are the three-dimensional analog of quadtrees.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The word is derived from *oct* (Greek root meaning "eight") + *tree*.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Octrees are often used in 3D graphics and 3D game engines.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Each node in an octree subdivides the space it represents into eight octants.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] In a point region (PR) octree (analogous to a point quadtree), the node stores an explicit three-dimensional point, which is the "center" of the subdivision for that node; the point defines one of the corners for each of the eight children.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] In a matrix-based (MX) octree (analogous to a region quadtree), the subdivision point is implicitly the center of the space the node represents.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The root node of a PR octree can represent infinite space; the root node of an MX octree must represent a finite bounded space so that the implicit centers are well-defined.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Note that octrees are not the same as *k*-d trees: *k*-d trees split along a dimension and octrees split around a point.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Also *k*-d trees are always binary, which is not the case for octrees.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] By using a depth-first search the nodes are to be traversed and only required surfaces are to be viewed.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] A spatial subdivision much like an octree was used in 1934, in the Whitney covering lemma in mathematics.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The octree color quantization algorithm, invented by Gervautz and Purgathofer in 1988, encodes image color data as an octree up to nine levels deep.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Octrees are used because $2^{3}=8$ and there are three color components in the RGB system.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The node index to branch out from at the top level is determined by a formula that uses the most significant bits of the red, green, and blue color components, e.g.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The next lower level uses the next bit significance, and so on.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Less significant bits are sometimes ignored to reduce the tree size.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The algorithm is highly memory efficient because the tree's size can be limited.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The bottom level of the octree consists of leaf nodes that accrue color data not represented in the tree; these nodes initially contain single bits.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] If much more than the desired number of palette colors are entered into the octree, its size can be continually reduced by seeking out a bottom-level node and averaging its bit data up into a leaf node, pruning part of the tree.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Once sampling is complete, exploring all routes in the tree down to the leaf nodes, taking note of the bits along the way, will yield approximately the required number of colors.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The example recursive algorithm outline below (MATLAB syntax) decomposes an array of 3-dimensional points into octree style bins.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The implementation begins with a single bin surrounding all given points, which then recursively subdivides into its 8 octree regions.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Recursion is stopped when a given exit condition is met.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Taking the full list of colors of a 24-bit RGB image as point input to the Octree point decomposition implementation outlined above, the following example show the results of octree color quantization.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] The first image is the original (532818 distinct colors), while the second is the quantized image (184 distinct colors) using octree decomposition, with each pixel assigned the color at the center of the octree bin in which it falls.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/octree] Alternatively, final colors could be chosen at the centroid of all colors in each octree bin, however this added computation has very little effect on the visual result.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The term "Ray Casting" was introduced by Scott Roth while at the General Motors Research Labs from 1978–1980.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] His paper, "Ray Casting for Modeling Solids", describes modeled solid objects by combining primitive solids, such as blocks and cylinders, using the set operators union (+), intersection (&), and difference (−).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The general idea of using these binary operators for solid modeling is largely due to Voelcker and Requicha's geometric modelling group at the University of Rochester.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Before ray casting (and ray tracing), computer graphics algorithms projected surfaces or edges (e.g., lines) from the 3D world to the image plane where visibility logic had to be applied.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The world-to-image plane projection is a 3D homogeneous coordinate system transformation, also known as 3D projection, affine transformation, or projective transform (homography).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Rendering an image this way is difficult to achieve with hidden surface/edge removal.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Plus, silhouettes of curved surfaces have to be explicitly solved for whereas it is an implicit by-product of ray casting, so there is no need to explicitly solve for it whenever the view changes.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Ray casting greatly simplified image rendering of 3D objects and scenes because a line transforms to a line.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] So, instead of projecting curved edges and surfaces in the 3D scene to the 2D image plane, transformed lines (rays) are intersected with the objects in the scene.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] A homogeneous coordinate transformation is represented by a 4×4 matrix.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The mathematical technique is common to computer graphics and geometric modeling.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] A transform includes rotations around the three axes, independent scaling along the axes, translations in 3D, and even skewing.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Transforms are easily concatenated via matrix arithmetic.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For use with a 4×4 matrix, a point is represented by [*X*, *Y*, *Z*, 1], and a direction vector is represented by [*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*, 0].
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Ray casting is the most basic of many computer graphics rendering algorithms that use the geometric algorithm of ray tracing.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Ray tracing-based rendering algorithms operate in image order to render three-dimensional scenes to two-dimensional images.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Geometric rays are traced from the eye of the observer to sample the light (radiance) travelling toward the observer from the ray direction.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The speed and simplicity of ray casting comes from computing the color of the light without recursively tracing additional rays that sample the radiance incident on the point that the ray hit.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This eliminates the possibility of accurately rendering reflections, refractions, or the natural falloff of shadows; however all of these elements can be faked to a degree, by creative use of texture maps or other methods.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The high speed of calculation made ray casting a handy rendering method in early real-time 3D video games.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The idea behind ray casting is to trace rays from the eye, one per pixel, and find the closest object blocking the path of that ray—think of an image as a screen-door, with each square in the screen being a pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This is then the object the eye sees through that pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Using the material properties and the effect of the lights in the scene, this algorithm can determine the shading of this object.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The simplifying assumption is made that if a surface faces a light, the light will reach that surface and not be blocked or in shadow.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The shading of the surface is computed using traditional 3D computer graphics shading models.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] One important advantage ray casting offered over older scanline algorithms was its ability to easily deal with non-planar surfaces and solids, such as cones and spheres.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] If a mathematical surface can be intersected by a ray, it can be rendered using ray casting.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Elaborate objects can be created by using solid modelling techniques and easily rendered.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Light rays and the camera geometry form the basis for all geometric reasoning here.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This figure shows a pinhole camera model for perspective effect in image processing and a parallel camera model for mass analysis.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The simple pinhole camera model consists of a focal point (or eye point) and a square pixel array (or screen).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Straight light rays pass through the pixel array to connect the focal point with the scene, one ray per pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] To shade pictures, the rays’ intensities are measured and stored as pixels.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The reflecting surface responsible for a pixel’s value intersects the pixel’s ray.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] When the focal length, distance between focal point and screen, is infinite, then the view is called “parallel” because all light rays are parallel to each other, perpendicular to the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Although the perspective view is natural for making pictures, some applications need rays that can be uniformly distributed in space.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For modeling convenience, a typical standard coordinate system for the camera has the screen in the X–Y plane, the scene in the +Z half space, and the focal point on the −Z axis.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] A *ray* is simply a straight line in the 3D space of the camera model.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] It is best defined in parameterized form as a point vector (*X*0, *Y*0, *Z*0) and a direction vector (*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] In this form, points on the line are ordered and accessed via a single parameter t.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] If the vector is normalized, then the parameter t is distance along the line.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Where n is the number of ray-surface intersections.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The ordered list of ray parameters, *t* [*i*], denote the enter–exit points.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The ray enters a solid at point *t* [1], exits at *t* [2], enters a solid at *t* [3], etc.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Point *t* [1] is closest to the camera and *t* [*n*] is furthest.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] In association with the ray parameters, the surface pointers contain a unique address for the intersected surface’s information.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The surface can have various properties such as color, specularity, transparency with/without refraction, translucency, etc.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The solid associated with the surface may have its own physical properties such as density.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This could be useful, for instance, when an object consists of an assembly of different materials and the overall center of mass and moments of inertia are of interest.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Three algorithms using ray casting are to make line drawings, to make shaded pictures, and to compute volumes and other physical properties.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Each algorithm, given a camera model, casts one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For computing volume, the resolution of the pixel screen to use depends on the desired accuracy of the solution.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For line drawings and picture shading, the resolution determines the quality of the image.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] To draw the visible edges of a solid, generate one ray per pixel moving top-down, left-right in the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Evaluate each ray in order to identify the visible surface *S* [1], the first surface pointer in the sorted list of ray-surface intersections.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] If the visible surface at pixel location (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* − 1, *Y* ), then display a vertical line one pixel long centered at (*X* − ½, *Y* ).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Similarly, if the visible surface at (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* − 1), then display a horizontal line one pixel long centered at (*X*, *Y* − ½).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The resulting drawing will consist of horizontal and vertical edges only, looking jagged in coarse resolutions.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Roth’s ray casting system generated the images of solid objects on the right.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Box enclosures, dynamic bounding, and coherence were used for optimization.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For each picture, the screen was sampled with a density of about 100×100 (i.e., 10,000) rays and new edges were located via binary searches.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Then all edges were followed by casting additional rays at one pixel increments on the two sides of the edges.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Each picture was drawn on a Tektronix tube at 780×780 resolution.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] To make a shaded picture, again cast one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This time, however, use the visible surface pointer S[1] at each pixel to access the description of the surface.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] From this, compute the surface normal at the visible point *t* [1].
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The pixel’s value, the displayable light intensity, is proportional to the cosine of the angle formed by the surface normal and the light-source-to-surface vector.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Processing all pixels this way produces a raster-type picture of the scene.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The volume (and similar properties) of a solid bounded by curved surfaces is easily computed by the “approximating sums” integration method, by approximating the solid with a set of rectangular parallelepipeds.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This is accomplished by taking an “in-depth” picture of the solid in a parallel view.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Casting rays through the screen into the solid partitions the solid into volume elements.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Two dimensions of the parallelepipeds are constant, defined by the 2D spacing of rays in the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The third dimension is variable, defined by the enter–exit point computed.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] where L is defined as the length of the direction vector.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Each ${\tfrac {t[i]\ -\ t[i-1]}{L}}$ is a length of a ray segment that is inside of the solid.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This figure shows the parallelepipeds for a modeled solid using ray casting.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This is a use of parallel-projection camera model.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This figure shows an example of the binary operators in a composition tree using “+” and “−” where a single ray is evaluated.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The ray casting procedure starts at the top of the solid composition tree, recursively descends to the bottom, classifies the ray with respect to the primitive solids, and then returns up the tree combining the classifications of the left and right subtrees.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This figure illustrates the combining of the left and right classifications for all three binary operators.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Ray casting is a natural modeling tool for making shaded pictures.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The grayscale ray-casting system developed by Scott Roth and Daniel Bass at GM Research Labs produced pictures on a Ramtek color raster display around 1979.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This figure shows a table scene with shadows from two point light sources.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Shading algorithms that implement all of the realistic effects are computationally expensive, but relatively simple.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For example, the following figure shows the additional rays that could be cast for a single light source.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For a single pixel in the image to be rendered, the algorithm casts a ray starting at the focal point and determines that it intersects a semi-transparent rectangle and a shiny circle.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] An additional ray must then be cast starting at that point in the direction symmetrically opposite the surface normal at the ray-surface intersection point in order to determine what is visible in the mirrored reflection.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] That ray intersects the triangle which is opaque.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Finally, each ray-surface intersection point is tested to determine if it is in shadow.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The “Shadow feeler” ray is cast from the ray-surface intersection point to the light source to determine if any other surface blocks that pathway.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The secondary ray is then processed as a specular ray.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For the refraction formula and pictorial examples, see Whitted’s paper.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Ray casting qualifies as a brute force method for solving problems.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The minimal algorithm is simple, particularly in consideration of its many applications and ease of use, but applications typically cast many rays.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Millions of rays may be cast to render a single frame of an animated film.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Computer processing time increases with the resolution of the screen and the number of primitive solids/surfaces in the composition.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] By using minimum bounding boxes around the solids in the composition tree, the exhaustive search for a ray-solid intersection resembles an efficient binary search.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The brute force algorithm does an exhaustive search because it always visits all the nodes in the tree—transforming the ray into primitives’ local coordinate systems, testing for ray-surface intersections, and combining the classifications—even when the ray clearly misses the solid.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] In order to detect a “clear miss”, a faster algorithm uses the binary composition tree as a hierarchical representation of the space that the solid composition occupies.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] But all position, shape, and size information is stored at the leaves of the tree where primitive solids reside.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The top and intermediate nodes in the tree only specify combine operators.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Characterizing with enclosures the space that all solids fill gives all nodes in the tree an abstract summary of position and size information.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Then, the quick “ray intersects enclosure” tests guide the search in the hierarchy.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] When the test fails at an intermediate node in the tree, the ray is guaranteed to classify as out of the composite, so recursing down its subtrees to further investigate is unnecessary.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Accurately assessing the cost savings for using enclosures is difficult because it depends on the spatial distribution of the primitives (the complexity distribution) and on the organization of the composition tree.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The following are miscellaneous performance improvements made in Roth’s paper on ray casting, but there have been considerable improvements subsequently made by others.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] If the operator at a composite node in the tree is − or & and the ray classifies as out of the composite’s left sub-solid, then the ray will classify as out of the composite regardless of the ray’s classification with respect to the right sub-solid.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] So, classifying the ray with respect to the right sub-solid is unnecessary and should be avoided for efficiency.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] By initially combining the screen-to-scene transform with the primitive’s scene-to-local transform and storing the resulting screen-to-local transforms in the primitive’s data structures, one ray transform per ray-surface intersection is eliminated.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Given a deep composition tree, recursion can be expensive in combination with allocating and freeing up memory.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Recursion can be simulated using static arrays as stacks.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] If only the visible edges of the solid are to be displayed, the ray casting algorithm can dynamically bound the ray to cut off the search.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] That is, after finding that a ray intersects a sub-solid, the algorithm can use the intersection point closest to the screen to tighten the depth bound for the “ray intersections box” test.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This only works for the + part of the tree, starting at the top.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] With – and &, nearby “in” parts of the ray may later become “out”.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The principle of coherence is that the surfaces visible at two neighboring pixels are more likely to be the same than different.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Developers of computer graphics and vision systems have applied this empirical truth for efficiency and performance.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For line drawings, the image area containing edges is normally much less than the total image area, so ray casting should be concentrated around the edges and not in the open regions.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This can be effectively implemented by sparsely sampling the screen with rays and then locating, when neighboring rays identify different visible surfaces, the edges via binary searches.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The jagged edges caused by aliasing is an undesirable effect of point sampling techniques and is a classic problem with raster display algorithms.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Linear or smoothly curved edges will appear jagged and are particularly objectionable in animations because movement of the image makes the edges appear fuzzy or look like little moving escalators.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Also, details in the scene smaller than the spacing between rays may be lost.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The jagged edges in a line drawing can be smoothed by edge following.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The purpose of such an algorithm is to minimize the number of lines needed to draw the picture within one pixel accuracy.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The line drawings above were drawn this way.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] To smooth the jagged edges in a shaded picture with subpixel accuracy, additional rays should be cast for information about the edges.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] (See Supersampling for a general approach.) Edges are formed by the intersection of surfaces or by the profile of a curved surface.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Applying "Coherence" as described above via binary search, if the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* + 1, *Y* ), then a ray could be generated midway between them at (*X* + ½, *Y* ) and the visible surface there identified.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The distance between sample points could be further subdivided, but the search need not be deep.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The primary search depth to smooth jagged edges is a function of the intensity gradient across the edge.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] For the history of ray casting, see Ray tracing (graphics) as both are essentially the same technique under different names.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Scott Roth had invented the term "ray casting" before having heard of "ray tracing".
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Additionally, Scott Roth's development of ray casting at GM Research Labs occurred concurrently with Turner Whitted's ray tracing work at Bell Labs.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] In early first person games, raycasting was used to efficiently render a 3D world from a 2D playing field using a simple one-dimensional scan over the horizontal width of the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Early first-person shooters used 2D ray casting as a technique to create a 3D effect from a 2D world.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] While the world appears 3D, the player cannot look up or down or only in limited angles with shearing distortion.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This style of rendering eliminates the need to fire a ray for each pixel in the frame as is the case with modern engines; once the hit point is found the projection distortion is applied to the surface texture and an entire vertical column is copied from the result into the frame.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] This style of rendering also imposes limitations on the type of rendering which can be performed, for example **depth sorting** but depth buffering may not.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] That is polygons must be full in front of or behind one another, they may not partially overlap or intersect.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The video game *Wolfenstein 3D* was built from a square based grid of uniform height walls meeting solid-colored floors and ceilings.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] In order to draw the world, a single ray was traced for every column of screen pixels and a vertical slice of wall texture was selected and scaled according to where in the world the ray hits a wall and how far it travels before doing so.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The purpose of the grid based levels was twofold — ray-wall collisions can be found more quickly since the potential hits become more predictable and memory overhead is reduced.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] However, encoding wide-open areas takes extra space.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The Raven Software game *ShadowCaster* uses an improved Wolfenstein-based engine with added floors and ceilings texturing and variable wall heights.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The Voxel Space engine developed by NovaLogic for the *Comanche* games traced a ray through each column of screen pixels and tested each ray against points in a heightmap.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Then it transformed each element of the heightmap into a column of pixels, determined which are visible (that is, have not been occluded by pixels that have been drawn in front), and drew them with the corresponding color from the texture map.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] Later DOS games like *id Software's DOOM* kept many of the raycasting 2.5D restrictions for speed but went on to switch to alternative rendering techniques (like BSP), making them no longer raycasting engines.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] The problem has been investigated for various settings: space dimension, types of objects, restrictions on query rays, etc.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/ray-casting] One technique is to use a sparse voxel octree.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] A **sparse voxel octree** (**SVO**) is a hierarchical octree data structure in which voxels recursively subdivide space into octants, storing only occupied or surface-intersecting regions, making it compact for raycasting and sometimes ray tracing in 3D computer graphics rendering.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] The technique generally relies on generating and processing the hull of points (sparse voxels) which are visible, or may be visible, given the resolution and size of the screen.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] There are two main advantages to the technique.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] The first is that only pixels that will be displayed are computed, with the screen resolution limiting the level of detail required; this limits computational cost during rendering.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] The second is that interior voxels (those fully enclosed by other voxels) need not be included in the 3D data set; this limits the amount of 3D voxel data (and thus storage space) required for realistic, high-resolution digital models and/or environments.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] The basic advantage of octrees is that, as a hierarchical data structure, they need not be explored to their full depth.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] This means that a system can extract a small subset of voxels as they are needed.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] In addition, octrees permit smoothing of the underlying data, to help with antialiasing.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] It is, however, a generally less well developed technique than standard polygon-based rasterisation schemes.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] As scenes grow in geometric complexity, SVOs have been proposed to facilitate a transition from traditional triangle-based pipelines to voxel-based rendering.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] Each non-leaf node in an SVO subdivides its voxel into eight child slots of equal size.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] Implementations such as efficient sparse voxel octrees encode which child slots exist and which are leaves with bitmasks, together with a child pointer for non-leaf descendants, so rays can traverse only relevant children instead of empty space.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/sparse-voxel-octree] SVOs support seamless level of detail (LOD) by storing pre-filtered geometry and appearance data at each level, allowing ray casting to terminate early when voxel size matches screen resolution.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] In scientific visualization and computer graphics, **volume rendering** is a set of techniques used to display a 2D projection of a 3D discretely sampled data set, typically a 3D scalar field.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] A typical 3D data set is a group of 2D slice images acquired by a CT, MRI, or MicroCT scanner.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Usually these are acquired in a regular pattern (e.g., one slice for each millimeter of depth) and usually have a regular number of image pixels in a regular pattern.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This is an example of a regular volumetric grid, with each volume element, or voxel represented by a single value that is obtained by sampling the immediate area surrounding the voxel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] To render a 2D projection of the 3D data set, one first needs to define a camera in space relative to the volume.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Also, one needs to define the opacity and color of every voxel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This is usually defined using an RGBA (for red, green, blue, alpha) transfer function that defines the RGBA value for every possible voxel value.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] For example, a volume may be viewed by extracting isosurfaces (surfaces of equal values) from the volume and rendering them as polygonal meshes or by rendering the volume directly as a block of data.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The marching cubes algorithm is a common technique for extracting an isosurface from volume data.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Direct volume rendering is a computationally intensive task that may be performed in several ways.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Another method of volume rendering is Ray marching, a category of 3D computer graphics rendering techniques in which rays are traced step by step, subdividing each ray into smaller segments and sampling a function at each interval.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Volume rendering is distinguished from thin slice tomography presentations, and is also generally distinguished from projections of 3D models, including maximum intensity projection.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Still, technically, all volume renderings become projections when viewed on a 2-dimensional display, making the distinction between projections and volume renderings a bit vague.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Nevertheless, the epitomes of volume rendering models feature a mix of for example coloring and shading in order to create realistic and/or observable representations.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] A direct volume renderer requires every sample value to be mapped to opacity and a color.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This is done with a "transfer function" which can be a simple ramp, a piecewise linear function or an arbitrary table.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Once converted to an RGBA color model (for red, green, blue, alpha) value, the composed RGBA result is projected on the corresponding pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The way this is done depends on the rendering technique.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] A combination of these techniques is possible.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] For instance, a shear warp implementation could use texturing hardware to draw the aligned slices in the off-screen buffer.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The technique of volume ray casting can be derived directly from the rendering equation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] It provides results of very high quality, usually considered to provide the best image quality.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Volume ray casting is classified as image based volume rendering technique, as the computation emanates from the output image, not the input volume data as is the case with object based techniques.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] In this technique, a ray is generated for each desired image pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Using a simple camera model, the ray starts at the center of projection of the camera (usually the eye point) and passes through the image pixel on the imaginary image plane floating in between the camera and the volume to be rendered.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The ray is clipped by the boundaries of the volume in order to save time.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Then the ray is sampled at regular or adaptive intervals throughout the volume.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The data is interpolated at each sample point, the transfer function applied to form an RGBA sample, the sample is composited onto the accumulated RGBA of the ray, and the process repeated until the ray exits the volume.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The RGBA color is converted to an RGB color and deposited in the corresponding image pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The process is repeated for every pixel on the screen to form the completed image.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This is a technique which trades quality for speed.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Here, every volume element is splatted, as Lee Westover said, like a snow ball, on to the viewing surface in back to front order.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] These splats are rendered as disks whose properties (color and transparency) vary diametrically in normal (Gaussian) manner.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Flat disks and those with other kinds of property distribution are also used depending on the application.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The shear warp approach to volume rendering was developed by Cameron and Undrill, popularized by Philippe Lacroute and Marc Levoy.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] In this technique, the viewing transformation is transformed such that the nearest face of the volume becomes axis aligned with an off-screen image data buffer with a fixed scale of voxels to pixels.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The volume is then rendered into this buffer using the far more favorable memory alignment and fixed scaling and blending factors.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Once all slices of the volume have been rendered, the buffer is then warped into the desired orientation and scaled in the displayed image.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This technique is relatively fast in software at the cost of less accurate sampling and potentially worse image quality compared to ray casting.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] There is memory overhead for storing multiple copies of the volume, for the ability to have near axis aligned volumes.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This overhead can be mitigated using run-length encoding.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Many 3D graphics systems use texture mapping to apply images, or textures, to geometric objects.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Commodity PC graphics cards are fast at texturing and can efficiently render slices of a 3D volume, with real time interaction capabilities.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Workstation GPUs are even faster, and are the basis for much of the production volume visualization used in medical imaging, oil and gas, and other markets (2007).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] In earlier years, dedicated 3D texture mapping systems were used on graphics systems such as Silicon Graphics InfiniteReality, HP Visualize FX graphics accelerator, and others.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This technique was first described by Bill Hibbard and Dave Santek.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] These slices can either be aligned with the volume and rendered at an angle to the viewer, or aligned with the viewing plane and sampled from unaligned slices through the volume.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Graphics hardware support for 3D textures is needed for the second technique.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Volume aligned texturing produces images of reasonable quality.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The image quality degrades with coarse slice counts, though there is often a noticeable transition when the volume is rotated.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Due to the extremely parallel nature of direct volume rendering, special purpose volume rendering hardware was a rich research topic before GPU volume rendering became fast enough.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The most widely cited technology was the VolumePro real-time ray-casting system, developed by Hanspeter Pfister and scientists at Mitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories, which used high memory bandwidth and brute force to render using the ray casting algorithm.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The technology was transferred to TeraRecon, Inc. and two generations of ASICs were produced and sold.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Pixel shaders are able to read and write randomly from video memory and perform some basic mathematical and logical calculations.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] These SIMD processors were used to perform general calculations such as rendering polygons and signal processing.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] In recent GPU generations, the pixel shaders now are able to function as MIMD processors (now able to independently branch) utilizing up to 1 GB of texture memory with floating point formats.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] With such power, virtually any algorithm with steps that can be performed in parallel, such as volume ray casting or tomographic reconstruction, can be performed with tremendous acceleration.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The programmable pixel shaders can be used to simulate variations in the characteristics of lighting, shadow, reflection, emissive color and so forth.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Such simulations can be written using high level shading languages.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The primary goal of optimization is to skip as much of the volume as possible.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] A typical medical data set can be 1 GB in size.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] To render that at 30 frame/s requires an extremely fast memory bus.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Skipping voxels means less information needs to be processed.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Often, a volume rendering system will have a system for identifying regions of the volume containing no visible material.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This information can be used to avoid rendering these transparent regions.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This is a technique used when the volume is rendered in front to back order.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] For a ray through a pixel, once sufficient dense material has been encountered, further samples will make no significant contribution to the pixel and so may be neglected.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The use of hierarchical structures such as octree and BSP-tree could be very helpful for both compression of volume data and speed optimization of volumetric ray casting process.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Image segmentation is a manual or automatic procedure that can be used to section out large portions of the volume that one considers uninteresting before rendering, the amount of calculations that have to be made by ray casting or texture blending can be significantly reduced.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This reduction can be as much as from O(n) to O(log n) for n sequentially indexed voxels.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation also has significant performance benefits for other ray tracing algorithms.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation can subsequently be used to highlight or expose structures of interest.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] By representing less interesting regions of the volume in a coarser resolution, the data input overhead can be reduced.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] On closer observation, the data in these regions can be populated either by reading from memory or disk, or by interpolation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The coarser resolution volume is resampled to a smaller size in the same way as a 2D mipmap image is created from the original.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] These smaller volume are also used by themselves while rotating the volume to a new orientation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Pre-integrated volume rendering is a method that can reduce sampling artifacts by pre-computing much of the required data.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] It is especially useful in hardware-accelerated applications because it improves quality without a large performance impact.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Unlike most other optimizations, this does not skip voxels.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Rather it reduces the number of samples needed to accurately display a region of voxels.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] The idea is to render the intervals between the samples instead of the samples themselves.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] This technique captures rapidly changing material, for example the transition from muscle to bone with much less computation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Image-based meshing is the automated process of creating computer models from 3D image data (such as MRI, CT, Industrial CT or microtomography) for computational analysis and design, e.g.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] For a complete display view, only one voxel per pixel (the front one) is required to be shown (although more can be used for smoothing the image), if animation is needed, the front voxels to be shown can be cached and their location relative to the camera can be recalculated as it moves.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/volume-rendering] Where display voxels become too far apart to cover all the pixels, new front voxels can be found by ray casting or similar, and where two voxels are in one pixel, the front one can be kept.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] In computing, a **voxel** is a representation of a value on a three-dimensional regular grid, akin to the two-dimensional pixel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Voxels are frequently used in the visualization and analysis of medical and scientific data (e.g. geographic information systems (G.I.S.)).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Voxels also have technical and artistic applications in video games, largely originating with surface rendering in *Outcast* (1999).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] *Minecraft* (2011) makes use of an entirely voxelated world to allow for a fully destructible and constructable environment.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] **Voxel art**, of the sort used in *Minecraft* and elsewhere, is a style and format of 3D art analogous to pixel art.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] As with pixels in a 2D bitmap, voxels themselves do not typically have their position (i.e. coordinates) explicitly encoded with their values.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Instead, rendering systems infer the position of a voxel based upon its position relative to other voxels (i.e., its position in the data structure that makes up a single volumetric image).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Some volumetric displays use voxels to describe their resolution.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] For example, a cubic volumetric display might be able to show 512×512×512 (or about 134 million) voxels.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] In contrast to pixels and voxels, polygons are often explicitly represented by the coordinates of their vertices (as points).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] A direct consequence of this difference is that polygons can efficiently represent simple 3D structures with much empty or homogeneously filled space, while voxels excel at representing regularly sampled spaces that are non-homogeneously filled.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] This definition has the following advantage.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] If fixed voxel form is used within the whole model it is much easier to operate with voxel *nodal points* (i.e. three coordinates of this point).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Yet, there is the simple form of record: indexes of the elements in the model set (i.e. integer coordinates).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Model set elements in this case are *state parameters,* indicating voxel belonging to the modeled object or its separate parts, including their surfaces.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] The word *voxel* originated by analogy to "pixel", with *vo* representing "volume" (instead of pixel's "picture") and *el* representing "element"; a similar formation with *el* for "element" is the word "texel".
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] The term *hypervoxel* is a generalization of voxel for higher-dimensional spaces.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] A volume described as voxels can be visualized either by direct volume rendering or by the extraction of polygon iso-surfaces that follow the contours of given threshold values.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] The marching cubes algorithm(s) and Inertial frame of reference(s) are often used for iso-surface extraction, however other methods exist as well.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Both ray tracing and ray casting, as well as rasterisation, can be applied to voxel data to obtain 2D raster graphics to depict on a monitor.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Another technique for voxels involves raster graphics where one simply raytraces every pixel of the display into the scene, tracking an error term to determine when to step.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] A typical implementation will raytrace each pixel of the display starting at the bottom of the screen using what is known as a y-buffer.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] When a voxel is reached that has a higher y value on the display it is added to the y-buffer overriding the previous value and connected with the previous y-value on the screen interpolating the color values.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] There is a major downside to voxel rasterization when transformation is applied which causes severe aliasing.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] The advantage was the ability to rasterise using cheap integer calculations on a CPU without hardware acceleration.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] John Carmack also experimented with voxels for the *Quake III Arena* engine.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] One such problem cited by Carmack was the lack of graphics cards designed specifically for such rendering requiring them to be software rendered.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] A voxel represents a single sample, or data point, on a regularly spaced, three-dimensional grid.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] This data point can consist of a single datum, such as an opacity, or multiple data, such as a color in addition to opacity.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] A voxel represents only a single point on this grid, not a volume; the space between each voxel is not represented in a voxel-based data set.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Depending on the type of data and the intended use for the data set, this missing information may be reconstructed and/or approximated, e.g. via interpolation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] The value of a voxel may represent various properties.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] In C.T. scans, the values are Hounsfield units, giving the opacity of material to X-rays.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Different types of value are acquired from M.R.I. or ultrasound.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Voxels can contain multiple scalar values, essentially vector (tensor) data; in the case of ultrasound scans with B-mode and Doppler data, density, and volumetric flow rate are captured as separate channels of data relating to the same voxel positions.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] While voxels provide the benefit of precision and depth of reality, they are typically large data sets and are unwieldy to manage given the bandwidth of common computers.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] However, through efficient compression and manipulation of large data files, interactive visualization can be enabled on consumer market computers.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Other values may be useful for immediate 3D rendering, such as a surface normal vector and color.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Technologies to extend voxels into four and five dimensions of data are under investigation.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Uses of voxels include volumetric imaging in medicine and representation of terrain in games and simulations.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Voxel terrain is used instead of a heightmap because of its ability to represent overhangs, caves, arches, and other 3D terrain features.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] These concave features cannot be represented in a heightmap due to only the top 'layer' of data being represented, leaving everything below it filled (the volume that would otherwise be the inside of the caves, or the underside of arches or overhangs).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] While scientific volume visualization does not require modifying the actual voxel data, voxel editors can be used to create art (especially 3D pixel art) and models for voxel-based games.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Some editors are focused on a single approach to voxel editing while others mix various approaches.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] There are a few voxel editors available that are not tied to specific games or engines.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] They can be used as alternatives or complements to traditional 3D vector modeling.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] A generalization of a voxel is the *toxel*, or temporal voxel.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] This is used in the case of a 4D data set, such as an image sequence that represents 3D space together with another spatial dimension or a time dimension.
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] In this way, an image could contain 100×100×100×100 voxels, which could be seen as a series of 100 frames of a 100×100×100 volume image (the equivalent for a 3D image would be showing a 2D cross-section of the image in each frame).
[src:sparse-voxel-octree/voxel] Although storage and manipulation of such data requires large amounts of memory, it allows the representation and analysis of spacetime systems.
